Feature: the bc-emit work-done wrapper satisfies the reachability precondition for a TAG/release deliverable by the tag pointing at the expected lineage, NOT by the work_id appearing on origin/main HEAD

  Pins the release/tag-deliverable reachability MODE that lead-vhfa defect 1
  identifies as missing from the pre-emit gate, as a distinct path in the
  CLI-layer "bc-emit work-done" wrapper (ADR-036 D1/D2). The defect: the
  commit-on-origin-main precondition (scenario 177) assumes every deliverable is a
  work_id-attributed COMMIT reachable from origin/main HEAD. Release-mechanics
  maintenance produces a TAG (e.g. a vX.Y.Z bump pointing at a commit), and
  "origin/main" legitimately advances PAST that tag with later commits. So the
  work_id is correctly NOT on HEAD — the tag IS the deliverable. Without this mode
  the gate false-blocks legitimately-complete release work (lead-vhfa source:
  lead-if8q v0.2.5 tag, independently confirmed on the lead artifact surface, yet
  returned blocked).

  This feature pins that, for a TAG deliverable, reachability is satisfied by the
  tag existing and pointing at the expected commit lineage — NOT by requiring the
  work_id to appear on "origin/main" HEAD. The wrapper must offer this as an
  explicit mode so a vX.Y.Z bump+tag is not false-blocked.

  Sharpened to answer the lead-m56e clarify (shopsystem-templates, against this
  scenario). The prior version pinned ONLY the positive arm — that a tag pointing
  at the expected lineage satisfies reachability — and asserted no negative. That
  left "points at the expected commit lineage" operationally vacuous: an
  implementation that accepts ANY existing tag whose "git rev-list" is non-empty
  passes the positive arm, because the work_id is never used to verify the tag's
  lineage (the BC's adversarial probe confirmed a tag pointing at the repo's
  unrelated seed commit satisfied the check). The second Scenario below adds the
  required negative arm so "expected commit lineage" is a real, work_id-anchored
  check rather than a non-empty-rev-list tautology. The discriminating difference
  between the two arms is the SAME tag-existence-and-non-emptiness state; what
  separates satisfy from refuse is solely whether the tag's commit lineage
  carries/anchors the dispatched work_id.

  The git checks run inside the BC container against the BC's own tree (ADR-036 D2,
  ADR-018), after a "git fetch origin --tags". "shop-msg respond" stays a pure
  messaging primitive; the bare "--force" path (scenario 181) remains the escape
  valve.

  @scenario_hash:12c98d2f7e5259a9
  Scenario: bc-emit work-done satisfies reachability for a TAG deliverable when the named tag exists and points at the expected commit lineage, even though origin/main HEAD has advanced past that commit
    Given a dispatched work_id whose deliverable is a release TAG that names an expected commit lineage
    And the named tag exists on "origin" after a "git fetch origin --tags" and points at the expected commit lineage
    And the BC's "origin/main" HEAD has legitimately advanced to a later commit that does NOT carry the work_id
    When the BC invokes the "bc-emit work-done" wrapper for that work_id in the TAG/release-deliverable mode
    Then the wrapper treats the reachability precondition as satisfied and does NOT refuse on the ground that the work_id is absent from "origin/main" HEAD
    And the satisfaction is established by the tag pointing at the expected commit lineage, not by the work_id being reachable from "origin/main" HEAD

  @scenario_hash:6d95d409dd527be6
  Scenario: bc-emit work-done REFUSES for a TAG deliverable when the named tag exists but points at a commit lineage that does NOT carry/anchor the dispatched work_id, naming both the tag and the work_id
    Given a dispatched work_id whose deliverable is a release TAG that names an expected commit lineage
    And the named tag exists on "origin" after a "git fetch origin --tags" and its "git rev-list" is non-empty
    But the commit lineage the tag points at does NOT carry or anchor the dispatched work_id — for example the tag points at the repository's unrelated seed commit that bears no relationship to the work_id
    When the BC invokes the "bc-emit work-done" wrapper for that work_id in the TAG/release-deliverable mode
    Then the wrapper exits non-zero and does not invoke "shop-msg respond work_done"
    And the wrapper's error names the tag-lineage-anchors-work_id precondition as the cause and names both the offending tag and the dispatched work_id
    And mere tag existence with a non-empty "git rev-list" does NOT satisfy the precondition; only a tag whose commit lineage carries/anchors the dispatched work_id satisfies it, so the positive arm above and this refusal differ solely on whether the tag's lineage anchors the work_id
